<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
        DELIBERATELY EMPTY.

        Earlier versions of this file claimed `com.apple.security.application-groups`
        and `keychain-access-groups` to mirror the GUI app. Those are *restricted*
        entitlements: macOS amfid requires an embedded provisioning profile to
        validate them, which app bundles carry and bare CLI binaries do not.
        Signing the CLI with those entitlements made amfid kill the binary on
        launch with `Error Code=-413 "No matching profile found"`.

        The CLI no longer claims any restricted entitlements. It still works
        because:

          - The App Group container directory at
            `~/Library/Group Containers/group.com.shawnbrown.file13/` is
            created by the GUI app on first launch. Any process owned by the
            same user can read/write that tree as plain filesystem paths.
            `FileManager.containerURL(forSecurityApplicationGroupIdentifier:)`
            still resolves the path even without the entitlement.

          - SwiftData store + UserDefaults suite + lock file all live inside
            that container, so they're reachable by the CLI.

          - Keychain entries are CLI-managed (default user keychain, no access
            group). The CLI's `accounts add` writes IMAP passwords there;
            future `providers set-key` will write API keys the same way. They
            do NOT mix with the GUI's access-group entries — running
            `file13 mail …` against an account added in the GUI will fail
            credential lookup. Re-add accounts on the CLI side to use them
            from headless context.

        If/when distribution moves to a `.pkg` installer with an embedded
        provisioning profile, restoring the App Group + Keychain entitlements
        becomes possible. Out of scope for the current Homebrew-tap path.

        **Update (2026-05-11):** the MAS-distributed app now bundles the CLI
        inside `File13.app/Contents/Resources/file13` (built by
        `scripts/embed-cli.sh`) and signs it with restored entitlements via
        `File13/File13-CLI.entitlements`. That variant shares the GUI's
        App Group container and keychain access group, so accounts added
        by the bundled CLI are visible to the GUI and vice versa. This
        file stays empty because the Homebrew-tap binary path (still
        served by `cli/Scripts/release.sh`) cannot carry a provisioning
        profile and would be killed by amfid if it claimed restricted
        entitlements.
    -->
</dict>
</plist>
